{"ts":"2026-06-27T01:50:37.362Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Developing Local Auth Preview**\n\nI'm making headway on a typesafe utility for a frontend-only local auth/session preview, housed in a new `lib/preview-auth.ts` file. My focus remains on avoiding server-side authentication, cookies, JWT, or Firebase, to keep things streamlined. The goal is a local, frontend-only preview layer for auth and sessions.\n\n\n**Mapping Roles to Permissions**\n\nI'm now diving into the `canAccessPortalSection` and `canAccessAdminSection` logic for my preview system. My primary focus is designing a sensible role-to-permission mapping within `lib/preview-auth.ts`. I'm working on a comprehensive matrix to define access levels for each defined role, ensuring clear and consistent permissions. Remember, this is frontend only!\n\n\n**Defining Access Levels**\n\nI'm now concretizing the user role definitions within `lib/preview-auth.ts`, laying out the permissions for each. I'm assigning explicit 'preview identity profiles' for each role like 'client_admin'. I'm aiming for a straightforward structure that maps each role to the appropriate access levels across different sections. I need to make sure the distinctions between roles are clear, especially with internal vs. external and admin vs. user roles.\n\n\n**Populating Mock User Profiles**\n\nI've just populated the mock identity profiles within `lib/preview-auth.ts`. I now have mock users for roles like client admin, client member, gff admin, operator, finance admin, support agent, and viewer. Each profile includes a name, email and unique label for use in the frontend-only preview system.\n\n\n**Defining Access Controls**\n\nI'm now determining access controls for `canAccessPortalSection` and `canAccessAdminSection` helper rules. My focus is crafting logic within `lib/preview-auth.ts`, based on the `clientSidebarLinks` for the client portal. I've defined initial roles and their appropriate access to sections like `dashboard`, `projects`, etc. I'll need to define role-based access for `/portal/*` routes, and plan to include route-level blocking that shows a \"Locked Preview State\" if permissions are not met, to aid in the frontend preview experience.\n\n\n**Implementing Access Logic**\n\nI'm now detailing access controls within `lib/preview-auth.ts` for the `/admin/*` routes. I'm carefully defining which roles—gff_admin, gff_operator, finance_admin, support_agent, viewer—can access specific sections like dashboard, clients, billing, and settings. I've excluded client roles entirely, and established helper functions such as `hasRole` to handle role-based permissions, alongside `getPreviewSession`, `setPreviewSession`, and `clearPreviewSession`.\n\n\n"}}
