{"ts":"2026-06-27T01:51:14.265Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Identifying Core Component**\n\nI've realized that `SecureLogin` is the core component handling the mock login state, as all logins render it directly. Diving back into `components/portal/SecureLogin.tsx`, I'm noting its current state, hoping to clarify how it functions. I'm focusing on its state structure right now.\n\n\n**Designing Interactive SecureLogin**\n\nI'm now thinking about how to make `SecureLogin` more engaging, given our new local auth/session preview. I want to add interactive simulated credential keys to make testing easier. I'm also thinking about a clear mock/simulation tag to distinguish this from the real authentication. Finally, I'll incorporate an interactive workflow to showcase the mock details based on the selected role.\n\n\n**Defining Role-Based Routing**\n\nI'm now determining role-based routing within the mocked login flow. Each role will trigger a scan animation and update `localStorage` with session details. The real challenge is the destination; I'm mapping client roles to `/portal/dashboard`, internal admin roles to `/admin/dashboard`, and giving the `viewer` role the choice of either route to keep it intuitive.\n\n\n**Refining Route Guard Logic**\n\nI'm now refining the `PreviewRouteGuard` component. I need it to handle situations where there's no preview session and when the session lacks permission. It must check for an active preview session, redirect to `/login` if none exists with a loading state, and render children if the session has access. Otherwise, I'll display a visually striking \"Locked Preview State\" or \"Access Restricted Enclave\" screen with the user's simulated role clearly displayed.\n\n\n**Enhancing Role Selector**\n\nI'm now integrating premium design into the role selection process. The goal is a top-bar dropdown displaying the current simulated role, offering access to all seven roles instead of the current two. Examining `components/private-app/role-switcher.tsx` shows how to turn a basic Client/Admin toggle into a beautiful popover with a role selector.\n\n\n**Implementing Role Selectors**\n\nI'm now implementing the role selector, aiming for a premium design with minimalist color indicators for each role (cyan, slate, red, purple, emerald, orange, gray). I'm incorporating \"MOCK\" or \"PREVIEW\" tags and displaying role titles with clearance summaries. Selecting a role triggers a scan overlay, sets the preview session, and redirects to `/admin/dashboard` or `/portal/dashboard` based on the role. This feels far more robust. I'm now checking the `ClientPortalLayout` and `AdminPortalLayout` to implement a similar effect.\n\n\n**Integrating Route Guard**\n\nI've determined that integrating the route guard logic within `ClientPortalLayout` and `AdminPortalLayout` is the cleanest approach, automatically protecting all sub-pages under `/portal` and `/admin`. This simplifies maintenance, as it's the simplest place for us to guard a whole sub-route. Now, I'm considering safe hydration, which requires managing local state to handle the server-side rendering phase safely, preventing potential mismatches. I'm adding `useState` hooks for `session` and `loading` within a `useEffect` hook to fetch the current session during the hydration phase, which is exactly how we prevent rendering mismatches.\n\n\n**Designing Route Guard**\n\nI'm now designing the `PreviewRouteGuard` component. It'll take `children` and a `type` prop for portal or admin routes. The component will check for an active session in local storage. If no session exists, it'll display a \"Session Required\" screen or redirect to `/login`. We can make this super premium, potentially with a countdown or redirect button, providing an experience that feels top-notch.\n\n\n"}}
